Regarded from this point of view, the poems of Tibullus are most valuable. There is nothing grand or noble about the mam—but much that is most lovable, even in his weakness. His worst fault is to have “loved not wisely, but too well.'' He thought better of Delia and Nemesis than they deserved. His verses are not always free from a languor which seems to betoken the excoesive sensibility of a delicate constitution. But his feeling is always genuine, and its expression direct and unaffected. As a fair example of his charac- teristics may Be taken the First Elegy os the First Book.
